{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654648"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18626"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18626"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11358"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62257"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10241"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26372"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are several muscles that control movement about the foot and an understanding of which muscles are primarily responsible for dorsiflexion and plantar flexion of the ankle joint is important.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is the primary dorsiflexor of the ankle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrocnemius","Peroneus brevis","Peroneus longus","Soleus","Tibialis anterior"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibialis anterior\u003C/strong\u003E is the main dorsiflexor of the ankle joint. It originates from the lateral surface of the tibia and inserts into the medial cuneiform and first metatarsal. When it contracts, it pulls the dorsum of the foot upwards towards the anterior shin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrocnemius\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a plantar flexor that forms the superficial part of the calf muscle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESoleus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle works with the gastrocnemius as a plantar flexor\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroneus longus\u003C/strong\u003E - While it contributes to plantar flexion, its primary action is foot eversion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroneus brevis\u003C/strong\u003E - Like peroneus longus, its main function is foot eversion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETogether, the gastrocnemius and soleus form the triceps surae complex, which is the primary plantar flexor group. The peroneal muscles primarily control eversion of the foot, with only a weak contribution to plantar flexion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tibialis anterior muscle is the primary dorsiflexor of the ankle joint.","The gastrocnemius and soleus muscles form the triceps surae complex, which is responsible for plantar flexion.","The peroneus longus and brevis muscles primarily evert the foot rather than dorsiflex or plantar flex."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62257"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18626"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia"